<sup id="cite_ref-DarkTide2_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DarkTide2-9" title=""><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> <a name="Today" id="Today"></a>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Boston_Molasses_Disaster&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Today">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Today</span></h2>
<p>The sites of the molasses tank and the North End Paving Company have been turned into a recreational complex, officially named Langone Park, featuring a <a href="/wiki/Little_League_Baseball" title="Little League Baseball">Little League</a> ballfield, a playground, and <a href="/wiki/Bocce" title="Bocce">bocce</a> courts.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10" title=""><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> Immediately to the east is the larger Puopolo Park, with additional recreational facilities.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11" title=""><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A small plaque at the entrance to Puopolo Park, placed by the Bostonian Society, commemorates the disaster.<sup id="cite_ref-bostonOnline_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bostonOnline-12" title=""><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> The plaque, entitled "Boston Molasses Flood", reads:</p>
<dl>
<dd>
<blockquote>
<p>On January 15, 1919, a molasses tank at 529 Commercial Street exploded under pressure, killing 21 people. A 40-foot wave of molasses buckled the elevated railroad tracks, crushed buildings and inundated the neighborhood. Structural defects in the tank combined with unseasonably warm temperatures contributed to the disaster.</p>
</blockquote>
</dd>
</dl>
